# Backend Architecture Strategy: Internal Gateway & ACL

## Architecture Diagram (Mermaid)

```mermaid
graph TD
    A[Frontend React] -- HTTPS / JWT --> B[Backend Spring Boot 4.x]
    B -- WebClient / OAuth2 --> C[Keycloak Auth]
    B -- WebClient / Circuit Breaker --> D[Identity Microservices]
    D -- API Call --> E[SEGIP / Gov Database]
    
    subgraph "Spring Boot Internal Components"
        B1[Security Filter Chain]
        B2[Identity Controller]
        B3[Anti-Corruption Layer - ACL]
        B4[Resilient Client]
        
        B1 --> B2
        B2 --> B3
        B3 --> B4
    end
```

## Strategy Components

### 1. Internal API Gateway
The Spring Boot backend acts as a single point of entry for the frontend, consolidating calls to multiple microservices (Auth, Identity, Validation). It handles authentication propagation (Token Relay).

### 2. Anti-Corruption Layer (ACL)
Integrates external API models into the bank's internal domain models. This prevents external API changes from breaking the entire frontend/backend business logic.

### 3. Resilience Layer
Uses Resilience4j to manage timeouts and retries for the SEGIP integration, ensuring the system remains stable even under external provider failure.

### 4. Observability Layer
Integrates Micrometer and OpenTelemetry for total visibility into the onboarding lifecycle.
